Unsupervise Learning Project - Customer Segmentation¶

Context

AllLife Bank wants improve their credit card customer business based on the input from market research. In order to do that they want to run personalized campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Also, their operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customer queries are resolved faster.

Objective

To identify different segments in the existing customer, based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank, using clustering algorithms, and provide recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers.

Data Dictionary

Sl_No: Primary key of the records

Customer Key: Customer identification number

Average Credit Limit: Average credit limit of each customer for all credit cards

Total credit cards: Total number of credit cards possessed by the customer

Total visits bank: Total number of visits that customer made (yearly) personally to the bank

Total visits online: Total number of visits or online logins made by the customer (yearly)

Total calls made: Total number of calls made by the customer to the bank or its customer service department (yearly)

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize)  # creating the 2 subplots
    
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet")  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    
    if bins:
      sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter")
    else: 
      sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2)  # For histogram
    
    ax_hist2.axvline(data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--")  # Add mean to the histogram
    
    ax_hist2.axvline(data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-")  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled countplots

def labeled_countplot(data, feature, hue=None, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    if hue==None:
      ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
      )
    else: 
      ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        hue=hue,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
      )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

5. K-Means Clustering¶

Finding appropriate number of clusters

K-means clustering technique requires to have number of clusters pre determined. To find the right number of clusters, let's use elbow method curve by taking clusters between 1 and 8.

In [60]:
clusters = range(1, 9)
meanDistortions = []  # Create a empty list

for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k)  # Initialize KMeans
    model.fit(ccdattrscaled)  # Fit kMeans on the data
    prediction = model.predict(ccdattrscaled)  # Predict the model on the data
    distortion = (
        sum(np.min(cdist(ccdattrscaled, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis=1))
        / ccdattrscaled.shape[0]  # Find distortion
    )

    meanDistortions.append(
        distortion
    )  # Append distortion values to the empty list created above

    print("Number of Clusters:", k, "\tAverage Distortion:", distortion)

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, "bx-")
plt.xlabel("k")  # Title of X-axis
plt.ylabel("Average Distortion")  # Title of y-axis
plt.title("Selecting k with the Elbow Method", fontsize=20)  # Title of the plot

In [61]:
sil_score = []  # Create empty list
cluster_list = list(range(2, 10))  # Creating a list of range from 2 to 10
for n_clusters in cluster_list:
    clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters)  # Initializing KMeans algorithm
    preds = clusterer.fit_predict((ccdattrscaled))  # Predicting on the data
    # centers = clusterer.cluster_centers_
    score = silhouette_score(ccdattrscaled, preds)  # Cacalculating silhouette score
    sil_score.append(score)  # Appending silhouette score to empty list created above
    print("For n_clusters = {}, silhouette score is {}".format(n_clusters, score))

plt.plot(cluster_list, sil_score)

1) all the clusters should have higher than average silhouette score - both are good. However, 3 does better than 4.

2) no negative silhouette coefficent value - both are good.

3) all the clusters should have different width - 3 shows clear different width in all the clusters, however, 4 has kind of similar in at least two of them.

4) all the clusters should have different silhouette score - 3 does that clearly, however 4 has two clusters (#1 and #3) with quite similar.

From above, it looks like 3 is a clear winner and it has better elbow and more silhouette score. I would like to apply number of clusters = 3 to k-means algorithm.

6. Hierarchical Clustering¶

Cophenetic Correlation and Dendograms

In hierarchical clustering, the cophenetic correlation and dendogram help us to determind what distance metric and linkage method to use and also how many clusters to use.

It is important to find the right distance metrics and the linkage method to use for the algorithm. In order to do that, let's take 4 different distance metrics and 4 different linkage methods and find the cophenetic correlation with each of the possible combination, which is 4x4=16.

In [74]:
# finding cophenetic correlation for total 16 combinations

# list of distance metrics
distance_metrics = ["euclidean", "chebyshev", "mahalanobis", "cityblock"]

# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "weighted"]

high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0, 0]

for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(ccdattrscaled, metric=dm, method=lm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(ccdattrscaled))
        print(
            "Cophenetic correlation for {} distance and {} linkage is {}.".format(
                dm.capitalize(), lm, c
            )
        )
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm

In [78]:
# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "centroid", "ward", "weighted"]

# lists to save results of cophenetic correlation calculation
compare_cols = ["Linkage", "Cophenetic Coefficient"]
compare = []

# to create a subplot image
fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(linkage_methods), 1, figsize=(15, 30))

# We will enumerate through the list of linkage methods above
# For each linkage method, we will plot the dendrogram and calculate the cophenetic correlation
for i, method in enumerate(linkage_methods):
    Z = linkage(ccdattrscaled, metric="euclidean", method=method)

    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i])
    axs[i].set_title(f"Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)")

    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(ccdattrscaled))
    axs[i].annotate(
        f"Cophenetic\nCorrelation\n{coph_corr:0.2f}",
        (0.80, 0.80),
        xycoords="axes fraction",
    )

    compare.append([method, coph_corr])

So whatever we have seen so far, I will prefer to go with distance metric of euclidean and linkage method of ward and with cluster size 4. The reason I chose ward even though its cohenetic coefficient is bit lower than other methods like complete or average because of much higher dendographic distance on y axis compare to any thing else. Also, cohenetic coefficient is not that low for ward, its not under 50% or something, its at 0.74 which is not that low.

As it was seen in dendogram of distance metric of euclidean and linkage method of ward, it could cut horizontally at any point to give number of clusters. To find out what is the best way to cut it to get the best number of clusters, let's check silhouette score of each cluster.

In [81]:
# find silhouette score for clusters 2 to 9 and visulaize it
sil_score = []  # Create empty list
cluster_list = list(range(2, 10))  # Creating a list of range from 2 to 10
for n_clusters in cluster_list:
    #clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters)  # Initializing KMeans algorithm
    clusterer =AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=n_clusters, affinity="euclidean", linkage="ward")
    preds = clusterer.fit_predict((ccdattrscaled))  # Predicting on the data
    # centers = clusterer.cluster_centers_
    score = silhouette_score(ccdattrscaled, preds)  # Cacalculating silhouette score
    sil_score.append(score)  # Appending silhouette score to empty list created above
    print("For n_clusters = {}, silhouette score is {}".format(n_clusters, score))

plt.plot(cluster_list, sil_score)

8. K-means vs Hierarchical Clustering¶

We have successfully done K-means and Hierarchical clustering in previous sections.

Let's compare both the techniques on different points below.

1. Time taken by each technique -

K-means - it was very quick, creating elbow curve, finding out silhouette score, apply to k-means algorithim, all took less than 10 seconds.
Hierarchical - it took much longer, finding Cophenetic correlation, creating dendograms, silhouette score, apply to hierarchical, all took almost 3 minutes.

2. Distinct clusters comparison -

K-means - tried with number of clusters as 3 and 4, and by checking their eblow and silhouette score, 3 turned out to be the best.

Hierarchical - tired different distance metrics and linkage and found linkage and eucledien distance the best and after checking silhouette scores of different number of clusters, 3 came out to be the best.

Both gave the best at number of clusters = 3

3. Silhouette Scores Comparison -

K-means - for 3 clusters, it came out 0.5157

Hierarchical - for 3 clusters, it came out 0.5147

Both were very close.

4. Observations in the similar clusters in both algorithms -

Both of the algorightms got 3 clusters, with very similar counts in each clusters. Both have cluster 0 with mid-range customers, cluster 1 with low-range customers and cluster 2 with high-range customers in terms of their credit limits and number of cards they carry. Also, both have highest counts in cluster 0 followed by cluster 1 and then cluster 2.

Overall, both the algorithms gave very close results in segmentaing customers.

9. Summary of Insights & Recommendations¶

As part of this project, we have analyzed the customer data of AllLife Bank who wants improve their credit card customer business. The objective of the project was to identify different segments in the existing customer, based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank, using clustering algorithms.

To achieve the goal, we tried k-means and hierarchical algorithms. We tried different methods to find best number of clusters based for these algorithms and segregated data into 3 different clusters. Both algorithms gave very close results.

While doing cluster analysis, I found that, mainly the clusters are segregated based on the way customer communicate with the bank. Customers can communicate via 3 ways.

1) Visting the bank in-person (cluster 0)

2) Visting the bank online (cluster 2)

3) By calling the bank (cluster 1)

Cluster 0 customers which like to visit the bank in-person are the maximum among any other clusters. They have mid range credit limit and number of credit cards which makes me guess these are middle class people with mid range income. These customers do not bring much business to the bank but as they are high in numbers its still profitable to the bank. To get more profit out of such customers, bank should think about reducing the overhead like keeping more stuff because of such customers. One way is to encourage them to use more online banking by advertising about it everytime they visit the bank, waive some fees if they do business online, setup automatic utility bill pays etc. so they get habit of using online. Also, bank can try to offer them good credit card rewards, huge points when sign up for new credit card, free family member credit card etc. so they use credit card more and bank can get more business. Bank should also look into the reasons behind their multiple visits, do they just visit to say pay bills or visit with some issues with their card or questions. Based on that, they can train their staff so customers visit less.

Cluster 2 customers visting online the most are the least in number, however they have maximum amount of credit limit and highest number of credit cards. These customers are the premium customers because they have more limits and cards so assuming these are higher income customers with better credit scores. And they use online resources of the bank and not actually human hours, so much less overhead to the bank. The bank should do their best to keep such customers. To upsell such customers, they could offer platinum kind of credit cards that has higher fees and has good rewards on luxury items/travels. Also, bank could keep improving their online website/app to they keep using without any complains.

Cluster 1 customers do maximum calls to the bank. These customers have the least credit limit and least total number of credit cards which makes me guess either they are low income customers or have poor credit history. Bank has little less 1/3rd customers like that. To get more business out of these customers which have bad credit score, bank should try to offer them pre-paid credit cards or provide credit card with a guarantor (with better credit history), that way no risk to the bank and customer can build the credit history. To get more out of low income, bank could offer better rewards or high bonus if they direct deposit etc. Also, bank needs to see the reasons behind the calls. If it is just to pay bills or issues with the card. Based on that bank can either train their staff or work on common issues, so customers do not need to call multiple times and they can retain their business.

Note - if dataset can get more features like customer's income and revenue to the bank, what kind of credit cards they have etc. then it would help to provide more in-depth recommendations to the marketing team.
